<p>
  In a series of blog articles, I am going to build methodologies to answer to this question. The keys are <strong>uncertainty</strong> and <strong>quantitative analysis</strong>.
</p>

<p>
  Financial engineering frameworks have a long history they dealt with uncertainty and quantitative analysis, so it will be interesting and effective to leverage the techniques built in the field.
</p>

<h2>The software industry has focused on <strong>"how"</strong> to build software better</h2>

<p>Instead of answering to the important question, <strong>"Do you want to invest in this project?"</strong>, the industry tried all the effort for better development methodologies.

<p>
  <ul>
    <li>Waterfall method</li>
    <li>Agile methodologies</li>
    <li>etc...</li>
  </ul>

  there has been so many different software development approaches.
  Some went well with wild success, but others tried the same approach and ended in painful failures
</p>

<p>
  You can see some of these methodologies <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Software_development_process">"Software development process" in Wikipedia</a> ).
</p>

<p>
  Lessons, best practices were learnt and shared from people who tried different approaches.
</p>

<h2>However, we still don't know <strong>"whether"</strong> to invest in a software project</h2>

<p>We still often ask an experienced developer for an estimate and it usually turns out inaccurate afterwards.</p>

<p>
  And there is the other equally important question we usually cannot answer.
</p>

<h2>Do you want to stop investing in this project?</h2>

